Shell startup files, and which one runs when.

When you log in or open a new shell, bash reads one or more startup files that set up your environment: your search path, your aliases, your custom prompt. Which files it reads depends on what kind of shell is starting, and getting this straight clears up a lot of confusion.

There are four files that matter. System-wide, there is the profile file under slash e-t-c, read by login shells for every user, and a system bash-r-c file read by interactive non-login shells. Per user, in your home directory, there is your bash-profile or profile file, read by your login shells, and your bash-r-c file, read by your interactive non-login shells. The key distinction is login versus non-login. A login shell is created when you log in at a console, s-s-h into a machine, or run s-u with the dash flag; it reads the profile files. An interactive non-login shell is what you get opening a new terminal window in a desktop, or running bash inside an existing shell; it reads the bash-r-c files. And a non-interactive shell running a script reads neither, simply inheriting its parent's environment.

Because that split is fiddly, there is a common tidy-up: people make their bash-profile simply source their bash-r-c, so that the bash-r-c runs in both login and non-login interactive shells, and many distributions set this up for you by default.

As for what goes where, the convention is this. Your bash-r-c holds aliases, shell functions, and prompt customisation, the interactive niceties. Your profile holds exported environment variables and path changes, things that need to happen once per login. The system profile and its drop-in directory hold system-wide login setup, where packages place their own scripts. After editing any of these, you either source the file to apply it immediately or open a fresh shell. These are the very dotfiles mentioned back when we discussed hidden files; now you know why they matter, because they are the per-user customisation layer behind every shell you open.
